        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I hear you, and I want to acknowledge how scared you must be feeling right now. When you're experiencing something that feels different and worse than your usual migraines, it's completely understandable to want answers and reassurance through testing. I apologize if my previous responses made you feel unheard - that wasn't my intention.\n\nYou're asking about the actual harm, and I want to be transparent about that. A CT scan would expose you to radiation (about the same as 100-200 chest X-rays), carries a small risk of allergic reaction to contrast if used, and may show incidental findings that could lead to additional testing and anxiety - even when those findings are ultimately benign. But more importantly, based on your history and symptoms, the likelihood of finding something that would change your treatment is very low.\n\nThat said, your anxiety is real and needs addressing. Let me be clear: if you absolutely insist on a CT scan, I can order it. But I want to make sure we also discuss what we'll do depending on the results. If it's normal, will that give you the reassurance you need? And if we find something unexpected, what would you want to do then?\n\nWould you be willing to try one thing first? While we arrange the scan, could we also start you on migraine-specific medications that might help relieve your symptoms more effectively than what you've tried? This way we're addressing both your immediate suffering and your need for reassurance."
