        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello, thank you for reaching out about your headache symptoms. I understand how debilitating a severe migraine can be, especially when it's more intense than your usual episodes.\n\nBased on your description of a throbbing, one-sided headache with nausea and light sensitivity - along with your history of migraines - this does appear to be a migraine episode. The American Academy of Neurology guidelines indicate that neuroimaging like a CT scan isn't typically needed for migraine headaches when there are no \"red flag\" symptoms present.\n\nInstead, I'd recommend focusing on migraine management strategies that might provide better relief than over-the-counter medications alone. This could include prescription medications specifically designed for migraines, resting in a dark, quiet room, applying cold packs to your head, and ensuring proper hydration.\n\nThat said, if you experience any of the following, please seek immediate medical attention:\n- A sudden, severe \"thunderclap\" headache\n- Any new neurological symptoms like weakness, numbness, or difficulty speaking\n- A stiff neck with fever\n- Any headache significantly different from your usual migraines\n\nWould you like to discuss specific migraine treatment options that might help with your current symptoms?"
