        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I understand your concern about the possibility of missing something serious, and I appreciate that you're being thorough about your health research.\n\nThe guidelines I'm referencing are actually based on extensive research that has studied thousands of patients with headaches similar to yours. These studies have consistently found that when patients have headache characteristics typical of migraine (like your throbbing, one-sided pain with nausea and light sensitivity) and have a normal neurological examination, the likelihood of finding a serious underlying cause that would require intervention is very low - less than 1%.\n\nThe studies you may have been reading that suggest otherwise often involve different patient populations or patients with additional \"red flag\" symptoms. For example, if you had developed a headache like this for the first time after age 50, had a sudden \"thunderclap\" onset, or had new neurological symptoms like weakness or confusion, then imaging would definitely be recommended.\n\nWhat I would recommend instead:\n1. A thorough neurological examination to carefully evaluate you for any subtle signs that might change our approach\n2. A discussion of stronger prescription medications that are specifically designed to treat severe migraines\n3. Consideration of preventive medications if your migraines are becoming more frequent or severe\n\nWould you be open to me explaining more about the medications that might help with your current severe symptoms? I want to make sure we address your discomfort while also providing care that's aligned with the evidence about what's most likely to help you."
