        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I understand why you might expect antibiotics - we live in an era where people often associate sinus issues with bacterial infections that require antibiotics. However, based on current medical guidelines, we typically reserve antibiotics for cases that meet specific criteria.\n\nThe most important thing is to prevent antibiotic resistance while still addressing your symptoms. What you're experiencing sounds frustrating, but at this point, antibiotics aren't the most appropriate treatment. This isn't about rushing or delaying care - it's about using the most effective treatment at the right time.\n\nLet's focus instead on what will help your body heal itself:\n- Continue using saline nasal rinses 2-3 times daily\n- Consider a decongestant like pseudoephedrine for short-term relief (7 days or less)\n- Apply warm compresses to your face for pain relief\n- Try elevating your head while sleeping\n\nIf within the next 48-72 hours you develop any of these warning signs - fever over 100.4\u00b0F, development of colored nasal discharge, worsening pain, or if your symptoms suddenly worsen after improving - please return right away. At that point, we can reassess and determine if antibiotics would then be appropriate.\n\nDoes this plan give you more confidence in managing your symptoms?"
