        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "I understand your frustration completely - when you're feeling worse each day, it's natural to want something definitive to stop it in its tracks. I hear how real and urgent this feels to you.\n\nYou're asking about the potential harm in trying antibiotics, and that's an important question. The main concerns with prescribing antibiotics when they're not needed include:\n- Side effects like diarrhea, nausea, or allergic reactions\n- Contributing to antibiotic resistance, which makes future infections harder to treat\n- Disruption of the body's natural bacterial balance\n- Cost and inconvenience\n\nHowever, I want to acknowledge your concern about waiting. Let me propose this compromise: I'll write a prescription for antibiotics now with specific instructions to only start them if:\n\n1. Your symptoms become severe (high fever, severe pain, or thick colored discharge)\n2. You develop facial swelling\n3. Your symptoms continue to worsen significantly over the next 24-48 hours\n4. You simply don't improve with the other treatments we discussed\n\nYou can fill the prescription now but hold onto it, and use it as a \"safety net\" if your symptoms meet any of those criteria. This gives you some control while still following appropriate antibiotic use guidelines.\n\nWould this approach work for you? You'd have the antibiotics available if needed, but we'd try to manage this without them first."
