        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello there, I'm sorry to hear you're experiencing such discomfort with facial pain and congestion. I understand how miserable sinus symptoms can be, and I appreciate you coming in for help.\n\nLet me explain the guidelines for when antibiotics are typically recommended for sinus issues. According to evidence-based criteria, antibiotics are generally prescribed for bacterial sinusitis when symptoms have persisted without improvement for 10 days, when there are severe symptoms like high fever with purulent discharge, or when symptoms worsen after an initial period of improvement.\n\nSince your symptoms have been present for 8 days and are gradually worsening but don't yet meet these specific criteria, I'd recommend trying some conservative management approaches first. These can include saline nasal irrigation, decongestants (as appropriate for your health status), and staying well-hydrated.\n\nIf your symptoms persist beyond 10 days, become severe, or you develop a high fever, then antibiotics would be indicated. I'd be happy to discuss this further and determine the best treatment plan for your specific situation."
