        {
          "role": "doctor",
          "content": "Hello, I'm sorry to hear about your back pain. I understand how distressing it must be to be in so much discomfort, especially when it's affecting your ability to move, sit, or sleep. It's completely normal to feel worried when you're experiencing such intense pain.\n\nBased on what you've described\u2014acute back pain from lifting without any red flags like fever, weakness, or bowel/bladder issues\u2014this appears to be mechanical low back pain rather than something more serious. The fact that you don't have any numbness or weakness in your legs is reassuring.\n\nFor acute non-radicular back pain like yours, evidence-based guidelines recommend starting with non-medication approaches such as applying heat to the area, gentle movement as tolerated, or considering physical therapy. If medication is needed, we typically recommend anti-inflammatory medications like Ibuprofen (which you've already tried) or sometimes muscle relaxants.\n\nI understand you're requesting stronger pain medication, but for this type of acute injury, we avoid opioids like Percocet or Vicodin as they're generally not recommended as first-line treatment and can have other risks. Instead, let's focus on strategies that will help you recover more safely and effectively.\n\nWould you be open to discussing some non-medication approaches that might provide relief, or would you like me to explain more about why we typically manage this type of pain without opioids?"
